 for bestpractices and # Content Editor

## Overview
Develop a complete Content Editor within LifeOps that enables end-to-end content workflows from idea to publish. The editor must support LLM-assisted writing, versioning, collaboration, and publishing integrations, while tying into a File Upload & Artifacts Storage system and a Content Pipeline Automation engine. The solution should provide a cohesive UX across the Content Editor page, a Content Dashboard, and a Content Calendar, with robust data integrity, audit trails, and security. All code and interfaces must be resilient to null/undefined values and follow runtime safety rules: use data ?? [] for Supabase results, guard all array methods, initialize useState with appropriate array/object types, validate API responses, and use optional chaining where appropriate.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Content Editor page is the primary, end-to-end workspace for creating, refining, and publishing content. It supports ideation, research, drafting, editing, scheduling, and publishing in a single integrated interface, with optional LLM-assisted writing, live collaboration, version history, and publishing connectors to channels (CMS, social, email, etc.).

Goals:
- Provide a fluid, distraction-minimized editor that lets teams move content through the lifecycle: idea → research → draft → edit → schedule → publish.
- Deliver real-time collaboration, autosave, and a robust LLM assistant pane for expansion, rewriting, tone adjustments, and structured prompts.
- Integrate version control (diffs, snapshots, revert), artifact/file attachments with lifecycle/versioning, and secure access to assets.
- Expose publish controls, metadata (SEO, tags), and channels with scheduling capabilities.
- Surface a cohesive view of pipelines, current drafts, review status, and performance insights via connected dashboards and calendars.

Features connected:
- File Upload & Artifacts Storage: Upload, store, and serve artifacts (run outputs, content attachments) with versioning and secure access. Ensure artifact metadata (version, creator, timestamp, access controls) is captured and auditable.
- Content Pipeline Automation: Orchestrate ideation, research, drafting, editing, scheduling, and publishing with LLM assistance and publishing connectors. Include per-step state, approvals, and traceable agent-to-agent handoffs in the orchestration layer.
- UI Panels:
  - Editor pane (WYSIWYG + Markdown toggle, autosave, and inline comments)
  - LLM Assistant Pane (suggestions, expansions, rewrite, tone controls)
  - Research Pane (linked sources, citation manager)
  - Versioning History (diff views, snapshots, revert)
  - Publish Controls (channels, schedule, metadata, and status)
- Connected Pages:
  - Content Dashboard: Overview for content pipelines, content calendar, drafts in progress, publishing status, pending approvals, and SEO/performance insights.
  - Content Calendar: Calendar-based scheduling UI for content items with publishing slots, drag-to-schedule, and conflict detection.

UI guidance:
- Follow the provided visual style: dark UI, high contrast for primary actions, restrained accents, and dense, information-rich panels optimized for power users.
- Ensure consistent typography, spacing, and component states as described in the design system.
- Provide keyboard accessibility, clear focus states, and responsive behavior for editor, panes, and dashboards.

Note: The API endpoints themselves are not specified in this task; the prompt should define the expected API contracts, data shapes, and integration points to accommodate future wiring to your backend, including Supabase or other data layers.

## Components to Build
1) Content Editor Page (Main Editor Surface)
- Subcomponents:
  - EditorWorkspace: canvas for content editing with WYSIWYG and Markdown toggle
  - LiveCollaborationPanel: cursors, presence indicators, per-section comments
  - AutosaveEngine: saves draft versions at configurable intervals; exposes save status
  - VersionBadgeStrip: shows current version, last modified, authors
  - LLMAssistantPanel: panel with prompts, tone controls, expansion, rewrite, summarize, and outline features
  - ResearchPanel: linked sources, citation manager, export/import citations
  - AttachmentsPanel: file upload area with drag-and-drop, artifact versioning, secure access tokens
  - PublishControlsPanel: channel selectors, scheduling UI, metadata (SEO, tags), publish vs. test run
  - DiffViewer: side-by-side or inline diffs between versions
  - HistoryPanel: historical diffs, snapshots, revert actions
- Data handling:
  - Draft content, versions, authors, timestamps
  - Attachments with versioning and access controls
  - Collaboration presence and comments tied to content piece
- Interactions:
  - Real-time collaboration (presence, cursors)
  - Tone/style controls; prompts to LLM; preview rendering
  - Autosave state indicators; manual save button
  - Validation for publish readiness (policy checks, approvals)

2) File Upload & Artifacts Storage Component
- Features:
  - Drag-and-drop and browse file picker
  - Versioning support per artifact (semver-like or timestamped)
  - Secure, revocable access tokens and per-user permission checks
  - Metadata: filename, mime type, size, uploader, version, createdAt
  - API surface: uploadArtifact(draftId, file, metadata) -> artifactId; fetchArtifact(artifactId) -> file blob/URL; listArtifacts(draftId) -> artifacts[]
- Safety:
  - Guard all results with data ?? [] when listing artifacts
  - Validate file types and size; enforce allowedMimeTypes
- UI/UX:
  - Thumbs/thumbnails, file type icons, version chips, download/view actions
  - Delete/replace/version bump with confirmation
- Data integrity:
  - Ensure artifact references are stored in a way that they survive draft version changes
  - Audit trail for artifact uploads, views, and shares

3) Content Pipeline Automation Orchestrator (LLM-assisted automation)
- Features:
  - Orchestrator that sequences steps: ideation, research, drafting, editing, scheduling, publishing
  - Agent-based handoffs with traceable messages
  - Prompt templates for each stage; variables for scope, audience, channel rules
  - Publishing connectors; ability to push to CMS, social, and email channels
  - Approvals queue integration with conditional auto-execute or require approvals
  - Constraints: max actions, spend limits, allowed tools, safety rails and required confirmations
  - Run history, logs, inter-agent traces, diffs, artifacts created
- API surface:
  - startPipeline(contentId, plan, scope) -> pipelineRunId
  - advancePipeline(runId, step, payload) -> updatedState
  - getPipelineState(runId) -> state including step, status, logs
  - requestApproval(runId, reviewerId) -> approvalId
  - publishToChannel(runId, channel) -> publishResult
- Data safety:
  - Validate all inputs; ensure all array-like data is guarded
  - Use Array.isArray checks and data ?? [] for lists
- UI integration:
  - Pipeline status widgets on Editor page and in Content Dashboard
  - Controls to pause/resume, rerun steps, view per-step diffs and logs

4) Content Dashboard Page
- Features:
  - Overview panels: content pipelines, drafts in progress, publishing status, pending approvals
  - SEO/performance insights: basic metrics with sparklines or small charts
  - Quick-create widgets to start ideation pipelines
  - Filters: status, author, channel, publish window
- Components:
  - PipelineSummaryCard: shows progress, ETA, last action
  - DraftListView: dense list with version, last updated, status
  - ApprovalsQueuePanel: items requiring review with approve/reject actions
  - SEOInsightsPanel: key metrics
- Data handling:
  - Lists of pipelines, drafts, approvals with null-safe mapping and guards
  - Use data ?? [] and Array.isArray() guards for all lists

5) Content Calendar Page
- Features:
  - Calendar UI with publishing slots
  - Drag-to-schedule items; conflict detection and resolution prompts
  - Views: month/week/day; thumbnails for each item
  - Quick actions from calendar: reschedule, edit, publish
- Components:
  - CalendarGrid: rendering of days/weeks with slots
  - ContentCardInCalendar: compact card with title, status, and tags
  - DragDropScheduler: handles dragging items between slots with conflict checks
  - ConflictDialog: informs user of conflicts and options
- Data handling:
  - Content items with publishDate, status, and channel metadata
  - Use guarded lists: (items ?? []).map(...) and Array.isArray checks

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Frameworks: React with TypeScript; state management via React hooks or a lightweight store
- Components:
  - EditorSurface with WYSIWYG and Markdown toggle
  - LLMAssistantPanel with configurable prompts (tone, length, style)
  - ResearchPanel with citation manager
  - AttachmentsPanel for artifact uploads
  - Versioning UI (diffs, snapshots)
  - PublishControlsPanel for channels, scheduling, and metadata
  - Dashboard widgets for Content Dashboard and Content Calendar
- State & Data Modeling:
  - useState<Type[]>([]) defaults for arrays; appropriate typing
  - Guards for all API results: consistently use data ?? [] and Array.isArray() checks
  - Persisted autosave keys per draft; reconcile on load
  - Real-time collaboration presence signals
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigable, screen-reader friendly labels
  - Focus traps for modals; ensure visible focus states
- Performance:
  - Debounced autosave; virtualization for long lists; pagination where needed
- Testing:
  - Unit tests for data helpers (guards), integration tests for API contracts, E2E flows for typical editor lifecycle

### Backend
- Data Models (drafts, versions, artifacts, pipelines, approvals, logs)
  - Draft: id, title, content, format (markdown/html), version, authorId, createdAt, updatedAt, isPublished
  - Version: id, draftId, content, diff, createdAt, authorId
  - Artifact: id, draftId, versionId, filename, mimeType, size, url, version, uploadedBy, createdAt
  - PipelineRun: id, draftId, planId, status, steps, logs, startedAt, endedAt
  - StepLog: id, runId, stepName, status, message, timestamp
  - Approval: id, runId, reviewerId, status, comments, requestedAt, decidedAt
- Endpoints (examples; ensure runtime safety)
  - POST /api/drafts with { title, content, format } -> Draft
  - GET /api/drafts/{id} -> Draft with data?. The response data may be null; validate
  - GET /api/drafts/{id}/versions -> Version[] | []
  - POST /api/drafts/{id}/versions with { content, note } -> Version
  - POST /api/drafts/{id}/artifacts with multipart/form-data -> Artifact
  - GET /api/drafts/{id}/artifacts -> Artifact[]
  - POST /api/pipelines with { draftId, plan, scope } -> PipelineRun
  - GET /api/pipelines/{runId} -> PipelineRun
  - POST /api/pipelines/{runId}/advance with { step, payload } -> PipelineRun
  - POST /api/pipelines/{runId}/approvals/{approvalId}/decide with { status, comments } -> Approval
  - POST /api/publish with { runId, channel, schedule } -> PublishResult
- Security:
  - JWT/OAuth authentication; authorization checks for write access to drafts, artifacts, pipelines
  - Access controls on artifacts (per-user/per-role)
  - Audit trails for all create/update/delete actions
- Validation:
  - Validate all inputs server-side; ensure arrays are validated via Array.isArray
  - Normalize API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Use nullish coalescing for optional fields

### Integration
- Data Flow:
  - Editor writes content -> autosave creates new DraftVersion; attach metadata
  - Attach artifacts uploaded in AttachmentsPanel are versioned and linked to draft/version
  - LLMAssistantPane executes prompts via an LLM service; results saved as Suggestions or Draft updates
  - Content Pipeline Automator consumes a Draft to create a PipelineRun; steps progress with logs and artifacts
  - PublishControlsPanel triggers publisher connectors; results saved to PipelineRun and PublishResult
- Synchronization:
  - Ensure consistent IDs across panels (draftId, versionId, runId)
  - When a draft version is created, all panels reflect the latest version; provide diffs against previous versions
- Reuse:
  - Centralized helper utilities for null-safe array handling, API response normalization, and date handling
  - Shared UI primitives: Button, Card, Tabs, Modal, Tooltip with styles aligned to the design system

## User Experience Flow
1) Idea → Research:
- User creates a new Draft with a title and initial idea summary.
- Editor autosaves to Draft, creates Version 1.
- LLM Assistant provides outline and expansion suggestions; user accepts/refines.
- ResearchPane collects sources; user marks citations; citations are linked to the draft version.

2) Draft Writing:
- User writes content in EditorSurface; Markdown toggle available; autosave continuously.
- Real-time collaboration shows collaborators editing the same draft.
- LLM Assistant suggests rewrites or tone adjustments; user applies changes.

3) Editing & Review:
- User triggers Edition pass; Versioned diffs are shown in DiffViewer.
- Reviewer/Collaborator adds comments; approvals queue is populated if needed.
- Version history stores snapshots; user can revert to prior version if necessary.

4) Artifacts & Attachments:
- User uploads artifacts (data runs, attachments) via AttachmentsPanel; artifacts are versioned and accessible via secure links.
- Artifact metadata is visible in the artifact list and can be attached to the draft version.

5) Scheduling & Publishing:
- PublishControlsPanel allows scheduling publish date/time and selecting channels (CMS, social, email).
- In Content Calendar, user drags a draft into a slot; conflict detection alerts if the slot is occupied.
- PipelineAutomation runs, logging steps; on success, content is published via connectors and status is updated.

6) Dashboard & Insights:
- Content Dashboard shows pipeline progress, drafts in progress, approvals, and SEO/performance metrics.
- Content Calendar provides a weekly/monthly view with color-coded statuses and quick actions.

7) Audit & Revisions:
- All actions produce an audit trail; users can view run logs, agent messages, and generated artifacts.
- Reverts and diffs are easily accessible; permissions ensure only authorized users can revert/publish.

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: Draft, Version, Artifact, PipelineRun, StepLog, Approval, PublishResult
  - Draft: id, title, content, format ('markdown'|'html'), currentVersionId, authorId, createdAt, updatedAt, isPublished, seoMetadata
  - Version: id, draftId, content, changeSummary, authorId, createdAt
  - Artifact: id, draftId, versionId, filename, mimeType, size, url, version, uploadedBy, createdAt
  - PipelineRun: id, draftId, planId, status ('pending'|'running'|'completed'|'failed'), startedAt, endedAt, summary
  - StepLog: id, runId, stepName, status, message, timestamp
  - Approval: id, runId, reviewerId, status ('pending'|'approved'|'rejected'), comments, requestedAt, decidedAt
  - PublishResult: id, runId, channel, success, details, publishedAt

- API Endpoints (illustrative; implement as per your stack)
  - Drafts
    - POST /api/drafts
    - GET /api/drafts/{draftId}
    - GET /api/drafts/{draftId}/versions
    - POST /api/drafts/{draftId}/versions
  - Artifacts
    - POST /api/drafts/{draftId}/artifacts
    - GET /api/drafts/{draftId}/artifacts
  - Pipelines
    - POST /api/pipelines
    - GET /api/pipelines/{runId}
    - POST /api/pipelines/{runId}/advance
  - Approvals
    - POST /api/pipelines/{runId}/approvals
    - POST /api/pipelines/{runId}/approvals/{approvalId}/decide
  - Publish
    - POST /api/publish

- Security
  - JWT/OAuth 2.0; middleware enforcing authorization on drafts, artifacts, pipelines
  - Per-resource permissions; audit logs for all mutations
  - Access controls for artifact downloads
  - Rate limiting for LLM prompts to avoid abuse

- Validation & Runtime Safety
  - Always guard arrays: const items = data ?? []; items.map(...) guarded with Array.isArray
  - API responses validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Optional chaining: obj?.property?.nested
  - Destructuring defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}
  - Use useState<Type[]>([]) for array state; useRef for mutable objects where needed
  - Supabase results: const items = data ?? [] per requirement

## Acceptance Criteria
- [ ] End-to-end user flows from idea to publish operate without runtime errors; drafts persist across sessions; autosave and versioning are functional
- [ ] LLM Assistant pane can generate, apply, and revert prompts; tone and style controls work; prompts honor content scope
- [ ] Attachment upload supports versioning, secure access, and per-artifact metadata; artifacts are retrievable and auditable
- [ ] Content Pipeline Automation can initialize a pipeline, progress through ideation, research, drafting, editing, scheduling, and publishing with proper logs and per-step statuses
- [ ] Scheduling/Calendar supports drag-to-schedule, conflict detection, and per-slot publishing actions
- [ ] Content Dashboard shows accurate counts, statuses, and SEO metrics; Approvals queue gates publish actions when required
- [ ] All API responses validated; all lists guarded with null-safe patterns; no runtime crashes due to undefined/null arrays

## UI/UX Guidelines
Apply the project's design system:
- Maintain the dark, dense, highly scannable UI with minimal accents
- Use the specified color palette for depth, status, and highlights
- Ensure typography hierarchy and spacing adhere to the 8px baseline grid and responsive rules
- Use rounded 8–12px radii for cards; 1px borders with rgba(255,255,255,0.03)
- Cards: elevated, gradient backgrounds, top icons, bold titles, metadata beneath
- Navigation: left sidebar with collapse/expand sections; active states marked with accent pill (#FF3B30)
- Data Visualization: subtle grids, consistent data colors from the accent palette
- Interactive Elements: responsive hover states, accessible focus outlines, and clear affordances for actions

## Visual Style

Color Palette and Typography are defined above; implement across components with a consistent theme:
- Font: Inter or SF Pro Display, fallback to Roboto
- Weights: headings 600–700, titles 500–600, body 400, microcopy 300–400
- Spacing: 8px grid; card paddings 16–20px; gutters 8–24px
- Layout: left sidebar width 220–260px; content area uses flexible grid

Key Design Elements (summary):
- Card Design: dark, rounded, gradient, subtle borders, hover lift
- Navigation: compact left rail with active accent pill
- Data Visualization: muted axes, colored lines/areas with restrained saturation
- Interactive Elements: primary/secondary actions, hover/focus states, toggles, chips, badges
- Transformations: smooth 120–200ms transitions, subtle shadows

## Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety
- Supabase query results: Always use nullish coalescing — const items = data ?? []
- Array methods: Guard all calls
  - (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
- React useState for arrays/objects: Initialize with proper type, e.g., useState<Type[]>([])
- API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Optional chaining: use obj?.property?.nested
- Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

